Problem:

We read a string into a fixed array (str), but we want to store it in dynamically allocated memory (v).

Solution 1 (Manual malloc + strcpy):

char str[101], *v;

scanf("%s", str);
v = malloc((strlen(str) + 1) * sizeof(char));  // +1 for '\0'
strcpy(v, str);

free(v);
âœ… Works, but easy to forget the +1.

Solution 2 (Using strdup):

char str[101], *v;

scanf("%s", str);
v = strdup(str);   // allocates + copies automatically

free(v);
âœ… Cleaner, safer, shorter.

ðŸ‘‰ Summary:

malloc + strcpy = manual, risk of bugs if you forget +1.

strdup = automatic, preferred.
